# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ambisonics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ambisonics/3d-audio-effect] 3-D audio (processing) is the spatial domain convolution of sound waves using head-related transfer functions.
[src:ambisonics/3d-audio-effect] It is the phenomenon of transforming sound waves (using head-related transfer function or HRTF filters and cross talk cancellation techniques) to mimic natural sounds waves, which emanate from a point in a 3-D space.
[src:ambisonics/3d-audio-effect] It allows trickery of the brain using the ears and auditory nerves, pretending to place different sounds in different 3-D locations upon hearing the sounds, even though the sounds may just be produced from only two speakers (dissimilar to surround sound).
[src:ambisonics/3d-audio-effect] Using head-related transfer functions and reverberation, the changes of sound on its way from the source (including reflections from walls and floors) to the listener's ear can be simulated.
[src:ambisonics/3d-audio-effect] These effects include localization of sound sources behind, above and below the listener.
[src:ambisonics/3d-audio-effect] Some 3D technologies also convert binaural recordings to stereo recordings.
[src:ambisonics/3d-audio-effect] 3D Positional Audio effects emerged in the 1990s in PC and video game consoles.
[src:ambisonics/3d-audio-effect] 3D audio techniques have also been incorporated in music and video-game style music video arts.
[src:ambisonics/3d-audio-effect] True representation of the elevation level for 3D loudspeaker reproduction become possible by the Ambisonics and wave field synthesis (WFS) principle.
[src:ambisonics/3d-audio-effect] Some amusement parks have created attractions based around the principles of 3-D audio.
[src:ambisonics/3d-audio-effect] One example is *Sounds Dangerous!* at Disney's Hollywood Studios at the Walt Disney World Resort in Florida.
[src:ambisonics/3d-audio-effect] Guests wear special earphones as they watch a short film starring comedian Drew Carey.
[src:ambisonics/3d-audio-effect] At a point in the film, the screen goes dark while a 3-D audio sound-track immerses the guests in the ongoing story.
[src:ambisonics/3d-audio-effect] To ensure that the effect is heard properly, the earphone covers are color-coded to indicate how they should be worn.
[src:ambisonics/3d-audio-effect] This is not a generated effect but a binaural recording.
[src:ambisonics/3d-audio-effect] Nick Cave's novel *The Death of Bunny Munro* was recorded in audiobook format using 3D audio.
[src:ambisonics/3d-audio-effect] The song "Propeller Seeds" by English artist Imogen Heap was recorded using 3D audio.
[src:ambisonics/3d-audio-effect] There have been developments in using 3D audio for DJ performances including the world's first Dolby Atmos event on 23 January 2016 held at Ministry of Sound, London.
[src:ambisonics/3d-audio-effect] The event was a showcase of a 3D audio DJ set performed by Hospital Records owner Tony Colman aka London Elektricity.
[src:ambisonics/3d-audio-effect] Other investigations included the Jago 3D Sound project which is looking at using Ambisonics combined with STEM music containers created and released by Native Instruments in 2015 for 3D nightclub sets.
[src:ambisonics/3d-audio-effect] In November 2024 it was announced that the US Air Force had awarded a $9 million contract to Danish defense company Terma A/S, to supply its 3-D audio system for the F-16 Fighting Falcon aircraft, with a program of upgrades over the next two years.
[src:ambisonics/3d-audio-effect] The system will provide high-fidelity digital audio by spatially separating radio signals, aligning audio with threat directions, and integrating active noise reduction.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] This page attempts to discuss the interaction of these constraints and their various trade-offs in theory and practice, as well as perceptional advantages or drawbacks of specific speaker layouts which have been observed in actual deployments.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] In its original formulation, Ambisonics assumed **plane-wave sources** for reproduction, which implies speakers that are infinitely far away.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] This assumption will lead to a pronounced bass boost for speaker rigs of small diameter, which increases with Ambisonic order.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] The cause is the very same proximity effect that occurs with directional microphones.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] Therefore, appropriate near-field compensation (bass equalisation) is beneficial.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] Distance does not affect the decoder matrix.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] Variable **speaker distance** is therefore the most important degree of freedom when deploying idealized layouts in actual rooms.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] It is constrained by the reverberation of the room which leads to uneven direct-to-reverb ratios between speakers at different distances, and the power handling capability of the most distant speaker.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] If speakers have to be moved very close, care must be taken to ensure they still cover the entire listening area with reasonably flat frequency response.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] For horizontal-only content, horizontal systems provide more stable localisation at high frequencies than full-sphere ones, as shown by a simulation of the energy vector ${\vec {r_{E}}}$ .
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] Therefore, if occasional horizontal-only reproduction at the highest precision is desired, full-sphere layouts with a dense horizontal ring are preferable.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] Since multiple speakers will inevitably radiate very highly correlated content, a moving listener may experience a **phasing effect** that affects the perceived timbre and can upset localisation.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] Phasing artefacts are most prominent in dry rooms on very precisely calibrated systems.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] They can be reduced by adding height speakers, which tend to smoothen the effect, or tuned to a subjective minimum by introducing staggered delays to the speakers, with the understanding that this may adversely affect low-frequency localisation if overdone.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] Phasing problems usually become evident in walk-around environments, and are of less concern for a seated audience, unless the interference pattern is so dense that it is perceived by small head movements.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] For multi-listener environments and auditoria, the **occlusion of speakers** by other listeners must not be under-estimated.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] Generally, the higher the order and the more physically accurate the reproduction, the more robust it is, up to the point where occlusion produces realistic effects that are consistent with the affected listener's visual perception.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] For low order systems however, reconstruction can easily fail entirely when line-of-sight to speakers is blocked, which has led to odd seating arrangements in listening tests.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] With-height systems usually provide more unhindered lines-of-sight per direction for a given audience, which might increase their robustness.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] Solvang and others have shown that using much more than the minimally required number of speakers can be detrimental.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] The reason is simple: more speakers with constant angular resolution means higher crosstalk and thus higher correlation between speakers.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] If not managed, this leads to stronger comb-filtering effect and phasing artefacts when the listener moves.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] Therefore, with some decoding techniques, it may be advisable to consider if and how a reasonably regular lower-order decoder that omits some speakers can be fitted into any higher-order system design.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] For example, the third-order octagon allows for a perfectly regular first-order square using only every other speaker.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] The literature is rife with horizontal decoders based on the simpler cylindrical harmonics, which do not depend on the elevation angle $\phi$ .
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] Their use is discouraged, because they wrongly assume cylindrical waves which would require perfect line sources for reproduction.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] Actual speakers are point sources and will inevitably leak energy along the vertical axis, which has consequences for near-field compensation and the tuning of dual-band decoders.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] Hence, cylindrical decoders do not usually fulfill the Ambisonic criteria.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] The theoretical minimum of speakers for horizontal playback is $2\ell +1$ , or the number of Ambisonic components.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] However, the triangle demonstrates that at least one more speaker is necessary for proper soundfield reconstruction, since it exhibits extreme *speaker detention*: when panned around, sounds will stick to speaker locations and then jump across to the next speaker, rather than showing uniform motion.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] As a consequence, the directions of ${\vec {r_{V}}}$ and ${\vec {r_{E}}}$ do not match between speakers, which causes localisation errors.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] Hence, the triangle is a suitable setup for Ambisonic reproduction only at low frequencies.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] Four-speaker setups are the most economical way of reproducing first-order horizontal material, and a rectangular layout is most easily fit into a living room, which makes these setups the most common in domestic environments.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] With rectangles, there is a localisation performance trade-off: the short sides will localise more stably than the square, the long sides worse.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] Consequently, for predominantly frontal sound stages, Benjamin, Lee, and Heller (2008) have observed a preference for rectangular layouts over squares.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] All legacy domestic hardware decoders supported rectangular layouts, usually with variable aspect ratios.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] It is tempting to consider 5.1 systems for Ambisonic playback due to their wide availability, but the ITU-R BS775 layout is quite hostile to Ambisonics due to its extreme irregularity.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] The three front speakers are so close together (-30°, 0°, +30°) that they will exhibit significant crosstalk in first-order, which causes irritating phasing artefacts without any benefit.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] Therefore, it is advisable to omit the center speaker and decode only for L, R, Ls and Rs, as has been done in all pre-decoded *G-format* releases for 5.1.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] These G-format disks also assume a rectangular layout.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] If first-order playback is desired, the rear speakers should be moved accordingly, otherwise the Ambisonic imaging will be very unstable due to the wide angle between the surround speakers.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] Decoding approaches to 5.1 were first suggested by Gerzon and Barton in 1992 and subsequently patented.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] Adriansen provides a free second-order decoder obtained by genetic search, and Wiggins (2007) has shown that source material as high as fourth order can be beneficial in order to 'steer' the decoding functions, even though the system is unable to reproduce the full spatial resolution.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] Second and third-order material can be played satisfactorily over the ITU 5.1 layout, but due to the problems with first-order reproduction, it should not be considered for Ambisonics except as a compromise when 5.1 content predominates.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] If six speakers and sufficient space are available, the hexagon is a very good option that has outperformed four-channel setups for first-order reproduction in listening tests and is capable of second-order reproduction.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] It can be driven by an inexpensive 5.1 sound card and domestic 5.1 amplifier, provided the LFE output is full-range.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] When used with one speaker in front, the hexagon can be abused for native 5.1 playback at the expense of a significantly wider and more blurry stereo stage (120° as opposed to 60° between L and R as per ITU-R BS775).
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] Alternatively, reasonably sharp virtual speakers at the canonical ITU locations can be created with second-order panners - this is an interesting option if a phantom center is tolerable, and it will also work with a two-in-front orientation, which leaves more room for a TV or projection screen.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] The Octagon is a flexible choice for up to third-order playback.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] When oriented one-in-front, it can be used for reasonably accurate native 5.1 playback (L and R at +/- 45° vs.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] 30°, and surrounds within the standardized sector at +/- 112.5°).
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] For first order, phasing artefacts might become obvious under non-reverberant listening conditions due to the use of significantly more speakers than required, and Solvang's results (2008) suggest slightly increased timbral defects outside the sweet spot.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] With eight channels, an octagon can be driven by affordable 7.1 consumer equipment, again as long as the LFE output is full-range.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] Driven in third order, it is a reasonable lower bound for concert sound reinforcement over an extended listening area, either for native Ambisonic content or to produce virtual speakers, which has been found to scale to several hundred listeners under favourable conditions.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] Stacked rings have been a popular way of obtaining limited with-height reproduction.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] Spatial resolution will be weak close to the zenith and nadir, but these are somewhat rare positions for sound sources.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] Rings are generally easier to rig than (hemi-)spherical setups because they do not require overhead trussing, speaker stands can be shared unless the rings are twisted, and entrances, fire escape routes etc. can be more easily accommodated for.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] Double hexagons and octagons are the most common variations.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] Since the introduction of #H#V mixed-order schemes by Travis (2009), stacked rings can be operated at their full horizontal resolution even for elevated sources. #H#V decoding matrices for common layouts are available from Adriaensen (2012).
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] Triple rings are rare, but have been used to good effect.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] Since stacked rings are somewhat wasteful at higher elevations and necessarily have a hole at the zenith, they have been largely surpassed by hemispherical layouts since mature methods for decoder generation have become available.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] As they are difficult to rig and require overhead points, hemispheres are usually found either in permanent installations or experimental studios, where expensive and visually intrusive trussing is not an issue.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] The regular Platonic solids are the only full-sphere layouts for which closed-form solutions for decoding matrices exist.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] Before the development and adoption of modern mathematical tools for the optimisation of irregular layouts and the generation of T-designs and Lebedev grids with higher numbers of speakers, the regular polyhedra were the only tractable options.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] Tetrahedral speaker setups were used in the 1970s for first trials of full-sphere sound reproduction.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] One such experiment conducted by the Oxford University Tape Recording Society was documented by Michael Gerzon in 1971.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] In this setup, the tetrahedron was inscribed into a cuboid, using every other corner.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] Despite Gerzon's somewhat over-enthusiastic description (which pre-dates the introduction of Ambisonics and the proper formulation of its psychoacoustic criteria), the tetrahedron exhibits the same stability problems in 3D that plague the triangle for horizontal-only reproduction.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] It is a viable option for adequate full-sphere reproduction only at low frequencies.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] The octahedron is difficult to set up in "upright" orientation, since the listener would occlude the floor speaker.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] Hence, a "slanted" setup is usually preferred.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] It provides basic full-sphere first-order reproduction for a single listener.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] Goodwin (2009) has suggested a slanted octahedron with separate front center (which he calls 3D7.1) as an alternative way of using 7.1 systems to achieve with-height Ambisonic reproduction in games, and to allow reasonably accurate native 5.1 playback.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] An OpenAL game audio backend and decoder for this setup is commercially available.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] The most commonly encountered full-sphere systems are cubes or rectangular cuboids.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] The same localisation trade-offs apply as for square vs. rectangle (see above).
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] Cuboids are easily fit into standard rooms and provide precise localisation in first order for a single listener plus enjoyable envelopment for one or two more, and they can be built using off-the shelf 7.1 components.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] If all speakers are placed in room corners, their acoustic loading and resulting bass boost will be uniform, which means they can all be equalised in the same way.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] For the sake of consistency, we consider the vertices of the regular polyhedra as speaker positions, which makes the twelve-vertex icosahedron the next in the list.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] If suitable rigging options are available, it is capable of second-order full-sphere reproduction.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] A good and slightly more practical alternative is a horizontal hexagon complemented by two twisted triangles on floor and ceiling.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] With twenty vertices, the dodecahedron is capable of third-order full-sphere playback.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] It is possible to decode Ambisonics and Higher-Order Ambisonics onto fairly arbitrary speaker arrays, and this is a subject of ongoing research.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] A number of free decoding toolkits as well as a commercial implementation are available.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] Higher-Order Ambisonics can be decoded to produce 3D stereo headphone output similar to that produced using binaural recording.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonic-reproduction-systems] This can be done in a number of ways, including the use of virtual loudspeakers in combination with HRTF data.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Unlike some other multichannel surround formats, its transmission channels do not carry speaker signals.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Instead, they contain a speaker-independent representation of a sound field called *B-format*, which is then *decoded* to the listener's speaker setup.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] This extra step allows the producer to think in terms of source directions rather than loudspeaker positions, and offers the listener a considerable degree of flexibility as to the layout and number of speakers used for playback.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Ambisonics was developed in the UK in the 1970s under the auspices of the British National Research Development Corporation.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Despite its solid technical foundation and many advantages, ambisonics had not until recently been a commercial success, and survived only in niche applications and among recording enthusiasts.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] In particular, it has proved an effective way to present spatial audio in Virtual Reality applications (e.g.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] YouTube 360 Video), as the B-Format scene can be rotated to match the user's head orientation, and then be decoded as binaural stereo.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Ambisonics can be understood as a three-dimensional extension of M/S (mid/side) stereo, adding additional difference channels for height and depth.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The resulting signal set is called *B-format*.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Its component channels are labelled W for the sound pressure (the M in M/S), X for the front-minus-back sound pressure gradient, Y for left-minus-right (the S in M/S) and Z for up-minus-down.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The W signal corresponds to an omnidirectional microphone, whereas $XYZ$ are the components that would be picked up by figure-of-eight capsules oriented along the three spatial axes.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] A simple Ambisonic panner (or *encoder*) takes a source signal S and two parameters, the horizontal angle $\theta$ and the elevation angle $\phi$ .
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Being omnidirectional, the W channel always gets the same constant input signal, regardless of the angles.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] So that it has more-or-less the same average energy as the other channels, W is attenuated by about 3 dB (precisely, divided by the square root of two).
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The terms for $XYZ$ actually produce the polar patterns of figure-of-eight microphones (see illustration on the right, second row).
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] We take their value at $\theta$ and $\phi$ , and multiply the result with the input signal.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The result is that the input ends up in all components exactly as loud as the corresponding microphone would have picked it up.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The B-format components can be combined to derive *virtual microphones* with any first-order polar pattern (omnidirectional, cardioid, hypercardioid, figure-of-eight or anything in between) pointing in any direction.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Several such microphones with different parameters can be derived at the same time, to create coincident stereo pairs (such as a Blumlein) or surround arrays.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] This virtual mic is *free-field normalised*, which means it has a constant gain of one for on-axis sounds.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The illustration on the left shows some examples created with this formula.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Virtual microphones can be manipulated in post-production: desired sounds can be picked out, unwanted ones suppressed, and the balance between direct and reverberant sound can be fine-tuned during mixing.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] A basic Ambisonic *decoder* is very similar to a set of virtual microphones.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] For perfectly regular layouts, a simplified decoder can be generated by pointing a virtual cardioid microphone in the direction of each speaker.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The signs of the X and Y components are the important part, the rest are gain factors.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The Z component is discarded, because it is not possible to reproduce height cues with just four loudspeakers in one plane.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] In practice, a real Ambisonic decoder requires a number of psycho-acoustic optimisations to work properly.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Currently, the All-Round Ambisonic Decoder (AllRAD) can be regarded as the standard solution for loudspeaker-based playback, and Magnitude Least Squares (MagLS) or binaural decoding, as implemented for instance in the IEM and SPARTA Ambisonic production tools.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Frequency-dependent decoding can also be used to produce binaural stereo; this is particularly relevant in Virtual Reality applications.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The spatial resolution of first-order ambisonics as described above is quite low.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] In practice, that translates to slightly blurry sources, but also to a comparably small usable listening area or *sweet spot*.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The resolution can be increased and the sweet spot enlarged by adding groups of more selective directional components to the B-format.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] These no longer correspond to conventional microphone polar patterns, but rather look like clover leaves.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The resulting signal set is then called *second-*, *third-*, or collectively, *higher-order ambisonics*.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] For a given order $\ell$ , full-sphere systems require $(\ell +1)^{2}$ signal components, and $2\ell +1$ components are needed for horizontal-only reproduction.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Historically there have been several different format conventions for higher-order ambisonics; for details see Ambisonic data exchange formats.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The B-format signals comprise a truncated spherical harmonic decomposition of the sound field.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] They correspond to the sound pressure W , and the three components of the pressure gradient $XYZ$ (not to be confused with the related particle velocity) at a point in space.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Together, these approximate the sound field on a sphere around the microphone; formally the first-order truncation of the multipole expansion.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] W (the mono signal) is the zero-order information, corresponding to a constant function on the sphere, while $XYZ$ are the first-order terms (the dipoles or figures-of-eight).
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] This first-order truncation is only an approximation of the overall sound field.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The *higher orders* correspond to further terms of the multipole expansion of a function on the sphere in terms of spherical harmonics.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] In practice, higher orders require more speakers for playback, but increase the spatial resolution and enlarge the area where the sound field is reproduced perfectly (up to an upper boundary frequency).
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] This area becomes smaller than a human head above 600 Hz for first order or 1800 Hz for third-order.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Accurate reproduction in a head-sized volume up to 20 kHz would require an order of 32 or more than 1000 loudspeakers.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] At those frequencies and listening positions where perfect soundfield reconstruction is no longer possible, ambisonics reproduction has to focus on delivering correct directional cues to allow for good localisation even in the presence of reconstruction errors.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The human hearing apparatus has very keen localisation on the horizontal plane (as fine as 2° source separation in some experiments).
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] At low frequencies, where the wavelength is large compared to the human head, an incoming sound diffracts around it, so that there is virtually no acoustic shadow and hence no level difference between the ears.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] In this range, the only available information is the phase relationship between the two ear signals, called *interaural time difference*, or *ITD*.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Evaluating this time difference allows for precise localisation within a *cone of confusion*: the angle of incidence is unambiguous, but the ITD is the same for sounds from the front or from the back.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] As long as the sound is not totally unknown to the subject, the confusion can usually be resolved by perceiving the timbral front-back variations caused by the ear flaps (or *pinnae*).
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] As the wavelength approaches twice the size of the head, phase relationships become ambiguous, since it is no longer clear whether the phase difference between the ears corresponds to one, two, or even more periods as the frequency goes up.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Fortunately, the head will create a significant acoustic shadow in this range, which causes a slight difference in level between the ears.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] This is called the *interaural level difference*, or *ILD* (the same cone of confusion applies).
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Combined, these two mechanisms provide localisation over the entire hearing range.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Gerzon has shown that the quality of localisation cues in the reproduced sound field corresponds to two objective metrics: the length of the particle velocity vector ${\vec {r_{V}}}$ for the ITD, and the length of the energy vector ${\vec {r_{E}}}$ for the ILD.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] In practice, satisfactory results are achieved at moderate orders even for very large listening areas.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Humans are also able to derive information about sound source location in 3D-space, taking into account height.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Much of this ability is due to the shape of the head (especially the pinna) producing a variable frequency response depending on the angle of the source.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The response can be measured by placing a microphone in a person's ear canal, then playing back sounds from various directions.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The recorded head-related transfer function (HRTF) can then be used for rendering ambisonics to headphones, mimicking the effect of the head.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] HRTFs differ among person to person due to head shape variations, but a generic one can produce a satisfactory result.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] In principle, the loudspeaker signals are derived by using a linear combination of the Ambisonic component signals, where each signal is dependent on the actual position of the speaker in relation to the center of an imaginary sphere the surface of which passes through all available speakers.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] In practice, slightly irregular distances of the speakers may be compensated with delay.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] True ambisonics decoding however requires spatial equalisation of the signals to account for the differences in the high- and low-frequency sound localisation mechanisms in human hearing.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] A further refinement accounts for the distance of the listener from the loudspeakers (*near-field compensation*).
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] A variety of more modern decoding methods are also in use.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Ambisonics decoders are not currently being marketed to end users in any significant way, and no native Ambisonic recordings are commercially available.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Hence, content that has been produced in ambisonics must be made available to consumers in stereo or discrete multichannel formats.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Ambisonics content can be folded down to stereo automatically, without requiring a dedicated downmix.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The most straightforward approach is to sample the B-format with a *virtual stereo microphone*.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The result is equivalent to a coincident stereo recording.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Imaging will depend on the microphone geometry, but usually rear sources will be reproduced more softly and diffuse.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Vertical information (from the Z channel) is omitted.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Alternatively, the B-format can be matrix-encoded into *UHJ format*, which is suitable for direct playback on stereo systems.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] As before, the vertical information will be discarded, but in addition to left-right reproduction, UHJ tries to retain some of the horizontal surround information by translating sources in the back into out-of-phase signals.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] This gives the listener some sense of rear localisation.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Two-channel UHJ can also be decoded back into horizontal ambisonics (with some loss of accuracy), if an Ambisonic playback system is available.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Lossless UHJ up to four channels (including height information) exists but has never seen wide use.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] In all UHJ schemes, the first two channels are conventional left and right speaker feeds.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Likewise, it is possible to pre-decode ambisonics material to arbitrary speaker layouts, such as Quad, 5.1, 7.1, Auro 11.1, or even 22.2, again without manual intervention.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The LFE channel is either omitted, or a special mix is created manually.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Pre-decoding to 5.1 media has been known as *G-Format* during the early days of DVD audio, although the term is not in common use anymore.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The obvious advantage of pre-decoding is that any surround listener can be able to experience ambisonics; no special hardware is required beyond that found in a common home theatre system.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The main disadvantage is that the flexibility of rendering a single, standard ambisonics signal to any target speaker array is lost: the signal is assumes a specific "standard" layout and anyone listening with a different array may experience a degradation of localisation accuracy.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Target layouts from 5.1 upwards usually surpass the spatial resolution of first-order ambisonics, at least in the frontal quadrant.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] For optimal resolution, to avoid excessive crosstalk, and to steer around irregularities of the target layout, pre-decodings for such targets should be derived from source material in higher-order ambisonics.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Ambisonic content can be created in two basic ways: by recording a sound with a suitable first- or higher-order microphone, or by taking separate monophonic sources and panning them to the desired positions.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Content can also be manipulated while it is in B-format.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] This is referred to as a *native* or *Nimbus/Halliday* microphone array, after its designer Dr Jonathan Halliday at Nimbus Records, where it is used to record their extensive and continuing series of Ambisonic releases.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] An integrated native B-format microphone, the C700S has been manufactured and sold by Josephson Engineering since 1990.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The primary difficulty inherent in this approach is that high-frequency localisation and clarity relies on the diaphragms approaching true coincidence.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] By stacking the capsules vertically, perfect coincidence for horizontal sources is obtained.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] However, sound from above or below will theoretically suffer from subtle comb filtering effects in the highest frequencies.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] In most instances this is not a limitation as sound sources far from the horizontal plane are typically from room reverberation.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] In addition, stacked figure-8 microphone elements have a deep null in the direction of their stacking axis such that the primary transducer in those directions is the central omnidirectional microphone.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Native arrays are most commonly used for horizontal-only surround, because of increasing positional errors and shading effects when adding a fourth microphone.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Since it is impossible to build a perfectly coincident microphone array, the next-best approach is to minimize and distribute the positional error as uniformly as possible.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] This can be achieved by arranging four cardioid or sub-cardioid capsules in a tetrahedron and equalising for uniform diffuse-field response.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The capsule signals are then converted to B-format with a matrix operation.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The Core Sound TetraMic was the first commercially available A-format ambisonic microphone.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Introduced in 2006, it uses four cardioid capsules.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Each TetraMic is individually calibrated, and a calibration file and A- to B-format encoder plug-in are provided with each microphone.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Outside ambisonics, tetrahedral microphones have become popular with location recording engineers working in stereo or 5.1 for their flexibility in post-production; here, the B-format is only used as an intermediate to derive virtual microphones.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Above first-order, it is no longer possible to obtain Ambisonic components directly with single microphone capsules.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Instead, higher-order difference signals are derived from several spatially distributed (usually omnidirectional) capsules using very sophisticated digital signal processing.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The Core Sound OctoMic was the first commercially available second-order ambisonic microphone.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Introduced in 2018, it uses eight cardioid capsules.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Each OctoMic is individually calibrated, and a calibration file and A- to B-format encoder plug-in are provided with each microphone.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The ZYLIA ZM-1 is a commercially available microphone capable of generating third-order ambisonic recordings, using 19 omni-directional capsules.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The em64 Eigenmike from mh acoustics is a 64-channel spherical microphone array capable of sixth-order capture.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The production of the em64 has superseded their previous em32 microphone.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The spacemic from Harpex Audio GmbH is an 84-channel double-sided planar array.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Current versions of its encoder as of late 2025 support fifth-order spherical capture.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] (subsequently patented) describes the use of bi-directional capsules for higher order microphones to reduce the extremity of the equalisation involved.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] No microphones have yet been made using this idea.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The most straightforward way to produce Ambisonic mixes of arbitrarily high order is to take monophonic sources and position them with an Ambisonic encoder.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] A full-sphere encoder usually has two parameters, azimuth (or horizon) and elevation angle.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The encoder will distribute the source signal to the Ambisonic components such that, when decoded, the source will appear at the desired location.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] More sophisticated panners will additionally provide a radius parameter that will take care of distance-dependent attenuation and bass boost due to near-field effect.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Hardware panning units and mixers for first-order ambisonics have been available since the 1980s and have been used commercially.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Today, panning plugins and other related software tools are available for all major digital audio workstations, often as free software.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] However, due to arbitrary bus width restrictions, few professional digital audio workstations (DAW) support orders higher than second.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Notable exceptions are REAPER, Pyramix, ProTools, Nuendo and Ardour.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] First order B-format can be manipulated in various ways to change the contents of an auditory scene.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Well known manipulations include "rotation" and "dominance" (moving sources towards or away from a particular direction).
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Additionally, linear time-invariant signal processing such as equalisation can be applied to B-format without disrupting sound directions, as long as it applied to all component channels equally.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] More recent developments in higher order ambisonics enable a wide range of manipulations including rotation, reflection, movement, 3D reverb, upmixing from legacy formats such as 5.1 or first order, visualisation and directionally-dependent masking and equalisation.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Transmitting Ambisonic B-format between devices and to end-users requires a standardized exchange format.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] While *traditional first-order B-format* is well-defined and universally understood, there are conflicting conventions for higher-order ambisonics, differing both in channel order and weighting, which might need to be supported for some time.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Traditionally, the *Furse-Malham (FuMa) higher order format* in the `.amb` container based on Microsoft's WAVE-EX file format.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] It scales up to third order and has a file size limitation of 4GB.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The current B-format standard format is AmbiX proposal, which adopts the `.caf` file format and does away with the 4GB limit.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] It scales to arbitrarily high orders and is based on SN3D encoding.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] SN3D encoding has been adopted by Google as the basis for its YouTube 360 format.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] To effectively distribute Ambisonic data to non-professionals, lossy compression is desired to keep the data size acceptable.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] However, simple multi-mono compression is not sufficient, as lossy compression tends to destroy phase information and thus degrade localization in the form of spatial reduction, blur, and phantom source.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Reduction of redundancy among channels is desired, not only to enhance compression, but also to reduce the risk of discernable phase errors.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] As with mid-side joint stereo encoding, a static matrixing scheme (as in Opus) is usable for first-order ambisonics, but not optimal in case of multiple sources.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] A number of schemes such as DirAC use a scheme similar to parametric stereo, where a downmixed signal is encoded, the principal direction recorded, and some description of ambiance added.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] MPEG-H 3D Audio, drawing on some work from MPEG Surround, extends the concept to handle multiple sources.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] MPEG-H uses principal component analysis to determine the main sources and then encodes a multi-mono signal corresponding to the principal directions.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] These parametric methods provide good quality, so long as they take good care in smoothing sound directions among frames.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] PCA/SVD is applicable for first-order as well as high-order ambisonics input.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] This section focusses on decoding of classic first-order ambisonics.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The Ambisonic B-format WXYZ signals define what the listener should hear.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] How these signals are presented to the listener by the speakers for best results, depends on the number of speakers and their location.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Ambisonics treats directions where no speakers are placed with as much importance as speaker positions.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] It is undesirable for the listener to be conscious that the sound is coming from a discrete number of speakers.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Some simple decoding equations are known to give good results for common speaker arrangements.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] But Ambisonic Speaker Decoders can use much more information about the position of speakers, including their exact position and distance from the listener.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Because human beings use different mechanisms to locate sound, **Classic Ambisonic Decoders** it is desirable to modify the speaker feeds at each frequency to present the best information using Shelf Filters.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Some views on the complexities of **Shelf Filters** and **Distance Compensation** are explained in "Ambisonic Surround Decoders" and "SHELF FILTERS for Ambisonic Decoders".
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] There are specialised decoders for large audiences in large spaces.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Hardware decoders have been commercially available since the late 1970s; currently, ambisonics is standard in surround products offered by Meridian Audio, Ltd.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Ad hoc software decoders are also available.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] This design is intended for a domestic, small room setting, and allows speakers to be arranged in diametrically opposed pairs.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] This design is intended for a domestic, small room setting.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The speakers are equidistant from the listener and lie equally spaced on the circumference of a circle.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The simplest Regular Polygon decoder is a Square with the listener in the centre.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Triangles do not work, exhibiting large "holes" between the speakers.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Regular Hexagons perform better than Squares especially to the sides.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] where $\theta _{n}$ is the direction of the speaker under consideration.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The most useful of these is the Square 4.0 decoder.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The coordinate system used in ambisonics follows the right hand rule convention with positive X pointing forwards, positive Y pointing to the left and positive Z pointing upwards.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Horizontal angles run anticlockwise from due front and vertical angles are positive above the horizontal, negative below.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] This design is intended for a large, public space setting.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] These are so named because the paper introducing deriving Ambisonic Decoders for irregular loudspeaker layouts was presented at the 1992 AES conference held in Vienna.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The design was covered by a 1998 patent. from Trifield Productions.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The technology provides one approach to the decoding of ambisonic signals to irregular loudspeaker arrays (such as ITU) commonly used for 5.1 surround sound replay.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The idea behind parametric decoding is to treat the sound's direction of incidence as a parameter that can be estimated through time–frequency analysis.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] A large body of research into human spatial hearing suggests that our auditory cortex applies similar techniques in its auditory scene analysis, which explains why these methods work.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The major benefit of parametric decoding is a greatly increased angular resolution and the separation of analysis and synthesis into separate processing steps.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] This separation allows B-format recordings to be rendered using any panning technique, including delay panning, VBAP and HRTF-based synthesis.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Parametric decoding was pioneered by Lake DSP in the late 1990s and independently suggested by Farina and Ugolotti in 1999.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Later work in this domain includes the DirAC method and the Harpex method.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The Rapture3D decoder from Blue Ripple Sound supports this and is already used in a number of computer games using OpenAL.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Since 2018 a free and open source implementation exists in the IEM Plugin Suite and the SPARTA suite that implement the recent academic developments and the sound codec Opus.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Opus provides two channel encoding modes: one that simply stores channels individually, and another that weights the channels through a fixed, invertible matrix to reduce redundancy.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] A listening-test of Opus ambisonics was published in 2020, as calibration for AMBIQUAL, an objective metric for compressed ambisonics by Google.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Opus third-order ambisonics at 256 kbps has similar localization accuracy compared to Opus first-order ambisonics at 128 kbps.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Since its adoption by Google and other manufacturers as the audio format of choice for virtual reality, ambisonics has seen a surge of interest.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] In 2018, Sennheiser released its VR microphone, and Zoom released an Ambisonics Field Recorder.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Both are implementations of the tetrahedral microphone design which produces first order ambisonics.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Atmos takes a fundamentally different approach in that it does not attempt to transmit a sound field; it transmits discrete premixes or stems (i.e., raw streams of sound data) along with metadata about what location and direction they should appear to be coming from.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The stems are then decoded, mixed, and rendered in real time using whatever loudspeakers are available at the playback location.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Higher-order ambisonics has found a niche market in video games developed by Codemasters.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Their first game to use an Ambisonic audio engine was Colin McRae: DiRT, however, this only used ambisonics on the PlayStation 3 platform.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Their game Race Driver: GRID extended the use of ambisonics to the Xbox 360 platform, and Colin McRae: DiRT 2 uses ambisonics on all platforms including the PC.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The recent games from Codemasters, F1 2010, Dirt 3, F1 2011 and Dirt: Showdown, use fourth-order ambisonics on faster PCs, rendered by Blue Ripple Sound's Rapture3D OpenAL driver and pre-mixed Ambisonic audio produced using Bruce Wiggins' WigWare Ambisonic Plug-ins.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] OpenAL Soft , a free and open source implementation of the OpenAL specification, also uses ambisonics to render 3D audio.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] OpenAL Soft can often be used as a drop-in replacement for other OpenAL implementations, enabling several games that use the OpenAL API to benefit from rendering audio with ambisonics.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] For many games that do not make use of the OpenAL API natively, the use of a wrapper or a chain of wrappers can help to make these games indirectly use the OpenAL API.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Ultimately, this leads to the sound being rendered in ambisonics if a capable OpenAL driver such as OpenAL Soft is being used.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The Unreal Engine supports soundfield ambisonics rendering since version 4.25.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The Unity engine supports working with ambisonics audio clips since version 2017.1.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] Most of the patents covering Ambisonic developments have now expired (including those covering the Soundfield microphone) and, as a result, the basic technology is available for anyone to implement.
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The system was ultimately licensed to Nimbus Records (now owned by Wyastone Estate Ltd).
[src:ambisonics/ambisonics] The "interlocking circles" Ambisonic logo (UK trademarks UK00001113276 and UK00001113277), and the text marks "AMBISONIC" and "A M B I S O N" (UK trademarks UK00001500177 and UK00001112259), formerly owned by Wyastone Estate Ltd., have expired as of 2010.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] The sound localization mechanisms of the mammalian auditory system have been extensively studied.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] The auditory system uses several cues for sound source localization, including time difference and level difference (or intensity difference) between the ears, and spectral information.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Other animals, such as birds and reptiles, also use them but they may use them differently, and some also have localization cues which are absent in the human auditory system, such as the effects of ear movements.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Animals with the ability to localize sound have an evolutionary advantage.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Sound is the perceptual result of mechanical vibrations traveling through a medium such as air or water.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Through the mechanisms of compression and rarefaction, sound waves travel through the air, bounce off the pinna and concha of the exterior ear, and enter the ear canal.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] In vertebrates, interaural time differences are known to be calculated in the superior olivary nucleus of the brainstem.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] According to Jeffress, this calculation relies on delay lines: neurons in the superior olive which accept innervation from each ear with different connecting axon lengths.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Some cells are more directly connected to one ear than the other, thus they are specific for a particular interaural time difference.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] This theory is equivalent to the mathematical procedure of cross-correlation.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] However, because Jeffress's theory is unable to account for the precedence effect, in which only the first of multiple identical sounds is used to determine the sounds' location (thus avoiding confusion caused by echoes), it cannot be entirely used to explain the response.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Furthermore, a number of recent physiological observations made in the midbrain and brainstem of small mammals have shed considerable doubt on the validity of Jeffress's original ideas.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Neurons sensitive to interaural level differences (ILDs) are excited by stimulation of one ear and inhibited by stimulation of the other ear, such that the response magnitude of the cell depends on the relative strengths of the two inputs, which in turn, depends on the sound intensities at the ears.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] In the auditory midbrain nucleus, the inferior colliculus (IC), many ILD sensitive neurons have response functions that decline steeply from maximum to zero spikes as a function of ILD.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] However, there are also many neurons with much more shallow response functions that do not decline to zero spikes.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Sound localization is the process of determining the location of a sound source.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] The brain utilizes subtle differences in intensity, spectral, and timing cues to localize sound sources.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Localization can be described in terms of three-dimensional position: the azimuth or horizontal angle, the elevation or vertical angle, and the distance (for static sounds) or velocity (for moving sounds).
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] The azimuth of a sound is signaled by the difference in arrival times between the ears, by the relative amplitude of high-frequency sounds (the shadow effect), and by the asymmetrical spectral reflections from various parts of our bodies, including torso, shoulders, and pinnae.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] The distance cues are the loss of amplitude, the loss of high frequencies, and the ratio of the direct signal to the reverberated signal.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Depending on where the source is located, our head acts as a barrier to change the timbre, intensity, and spectral qualities of the sound, helping the brain orient where the sound emanated from.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] These minute differences between the two ears are known as interaural cues.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Lower frequencies, with longer wavelengths, diffract the sound around the head forcing the brain to focus only on the phasing cues from the source.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Helmut Haas discovered that we can discern the sound source despite additional reflections at 10 decibels louder than the original wave front, using the earliest arriving wave front.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] This principle is known as the Haas effect, a specific version of the precedence effect.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Haas measured down to even a 1 millisecond difference in timing between the original sound and reflected sound increased the spaciousness, allowing the brain to discern the true location of the original sound.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] The nervous system combines all early reflections into a single perceptual whole allowing the brain to process multiple different sounds at once.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] The nervous system will combine reflections that are within about 35 milliseconds of each other and that have a similar intensity.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] In 1907, Lord Rayleigh utilized tuning forks to generate monophonic excitation and studied the lateral sound localization theory on a human head model without auricle.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] He first presented the interaural clue difference based sound localization theory, which is known as Duplex Theory.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Human ears are on different sides of the head, and thus have different coordinates in space.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] As shown in the duplex theory figure, since the distances between the acoustic source and ears are different, there are time difference and intensity difference between the sound signals of two ears.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] We call those kinds of differences as Interaural Time Difference (ITD) and Interaural Intensity Difference (IID) respectively.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] (ITD) between left ear (top) and right ear (bottom).
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] (ILD) between left ear (left) and right ear (right).
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] From the duplex theory figure we can see that for source B1 or source B2, there will be a propagation delay between two ears, which will generate the ITD.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Simultaneously, human head and ears may have a shadowing effect on high-frequency signals, which will generate IID.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] For frequencies below 800 Hz, the dimensions of the head (ear distance 21.5 cm, corresponding to an interaural time delay of 626 μs) are smaller than the half wavelength of the sound waves.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] So the auditory system can determine phase delays between both ears without confusion.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Interaural level differences are very low in this frequency range, especially below about 200 Hz, so a precise evaluation of the input direction is nearly impossible on the basis of level differences alone.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] As the frequency drops below 80 Hz it becomes difficult or impossible to use either time difference or level difference to determine a sound's lateral source, because the phase difference between the ears becomes too small for a directional evaluation.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] For frequencies above 1600 Hz the dimensions of the head are greater than the length of the sound waves.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] An unambiguous determination of the input direction based on interaural phase alone is not possible at these frequencies.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] However, the interaural level differences become larger, and these level differences are evaluated by the auditory system.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] This mechanism becomes especially important in reverberant environments.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] After a sound onset there is a short time frame where the direct sound reaches the ears, but not yet the reflected sound.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] The auditory system uses this short time frame for evaluating the sound source direction, and keeps this detected direction as long as reflections and reverberation prevent an unambiguous direction estimation.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] The mechanisms described above cannot be used to differentiate between a sound source ahead of the hearer or behind the hearer; therefore additional cues have to be evaluated.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Duplex theory shows that ITD and IID play significant roles in sound localization, but they can only deal with lateral localization problems.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] For example, if two acoustic sources are placed symmetrically at the front and back of the right side of the human head, they will generate equal ITDs and IIDs, in what is called the cone model effect.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] However, human ears can still distinguish between these sources.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Besides that, in natural sense of hearing, one ear alone, without any ITD or IID, can distinguish between them with high accuracy.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Due to the disadvantages of duplex theory, researchers proposed the pinna filtering effect theory.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] The shape of the human pinna is concave with complex folds and asymmetrical both horizontally and vertically.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Reflected and direct waves generate a frequency spectrum on the eardrum, relating to the acoustic sources.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Then auditory nerves localize the sources using this frequency spectrum.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] These spectrum clues generated by the pinna filtering effect can be presented as a head-related transfer function (HRTF).
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] The corresponding time domain expressions are called the head-related impulse response (HRIR).
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] The HRTF is also described as the transfer function from the free field to a specific point in the ear canal.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] where L and R represent the left ear and right ear respectively, $P_{L}$ and $P_{R}$ represent the amplitude of the sound pressure at the entrances to the left and right ear canals, and $P_{0}$ is the amplitude of sound pressure at the center of the head coordinate when listener does not exist.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] In general, an HRTF's $H_{L}$ and $H_{R}$ are functions of source angular position $\theta$ , elevation angle $\varphi$ , the distance between the source and the center of the head r , the angular velocity $\omega$ and the equivalent dimension of the head $\alpha$ .
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] At present, the main institutes that work on measuring HRTF database include CIPIC International Lab, MIT Media Lab, the Graduate School in Psychoacoustics at the University of Oldenburg, the Neurophysiology Lab at the University of Wisconsin–Madison and Ames Lab of NASA.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Databases of HRIRs from humans with normal and impaired hearing and from animals are publicly available.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] The human outer ear, i.e. the structures of the pinna and the external ear canal, form direction-selective filters.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Depending on the sound input direction, different filter resonances become active.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] These resonances implant direction-specific patterns into the frequency responses of the ears, which can be evaluated by the auditory system for sound localization.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Together with other direction-selective reflections at the head, shoulders and torso, they form the outer ear transfer functions.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] These patterns in the ear's frequency responses are highly individual, depending on the shape and size of the outer ear.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] If sound is presented through headphones, and has been recorded via another head with different-shaped outer ear surfaces, the directional patterns differ from the listener's own, and problems will appear when trying to evaluate directions in the median plane with these foreign ears.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] As a consequence, front–back permutations or inside-the-head-localization can appear when listening to dummy head recordings, or otherwise referred to as binaural recordings.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] It has been shown that human subjects can monaurally localize high frequency sound but not low frequency sound.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Binaural localization, however, was possible with lower frequencies.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] This is likely due to the pinna being small enough to only interact with sound waves of high frequency.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] It seems that people can only accurately localize the elevation of sounds that are complex and include frequencies above 7,000 Hz, and a pinna must be present.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] When the head is stationary, the binaural cues for lateral sound localization (interaural time difference and interaural level difference) do not give information about the location of a sound in the median plane.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Identical ITDs and ILDs can be produced by sounds at eye level or at any elevation, as long as the lateral direction is constant.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] However, if the head is rotated, the ITD and ILD change dynamically, and those changes are different for sounds at different elevations.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] For example, if an eye-level sound source is straight ahead and the head turns to the left, the sound becomes louder (and arrives sooner) at the right ear than at the left.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] But if the sound source is directly overhead, there will be no change in the ITD and ILD as the head turns.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Intermediate elevations will produce intermediate degrees of change, and if the presentation of binaural cues to the two ears during head movement is reversed, the sound will be heard behind the listener.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Hans Wallach artificially altered a sound's binaural cues during movements of the head.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Although the sound was objectively placed at eye level, the dynamic changes to ITD and ILD as the head rotated were those that would be produced if the sound source had been elevated.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] In this situation, the sound was heard at the synthesized elevation.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] The fact that the sound sources objectively remained at eye level prevented monaural cues from specifying the elevation, showing that it was the dynamic change in the binaural cues during head movement that allowed the sound to be correctly localized in the vertical dimension.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] The head movements need not be actively produced; accurate vertical localization occurred in a similar setup when the head rotation was produced passively, by seating the blindfolded subject in a rotating chair.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] As long as the dynamic changes in binaural cues accompanied a perceived head rotation, the synthesized elevation was perceived.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] In the 1960s Batteau showed the pinna also enhances horizontal localization.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] The human auditory system has only limited possibilities to determine the distance of a sound source.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] In the close-up-range there are some indications for distance determination, such as extreme level differences (e.g. when whispering into one ear) or specific pinna (the visible part of the ear) resonances in the close-up range.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Sound processing of the human auditory system is performed in so-called critical bands.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] The hearing range is segmented into 24 critical bands, each with a width of 1 Bark or 100 Mel.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] For a directional analysis the signals inside the critical band are analyzed together.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] The auditory system can extract the sound of a desired sound source out of interfering noise.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] This allows the listener to concentrate on only one speaker if other speakers are also talking (the cocktail party effect).
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] With the help of the cocktail party effect sound from interfering directions is perceived attenuated compared to the sound from the desired direction.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] The auditory system can increase the signal-to-noise ratio by up to 15 dB, which means that interfering sound is perceived to be attenuated to half (or less) of its actual loudness.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] In enclosed rooms not only the direct sound from a sound source is arriving at the listener's ears, but also sound which has been reflected at the walls.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] The auditory system analyses only the direct sound, which is arriving first, for sound localization, but not the reflected sound, which is arriving later (law of the first wave front).
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] So sound localization remains possible even in an echoic environment.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] This echo cancellation occurs in the Dorsal Nucleus of the Lateral Lemniscus (DNLL).
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] In order to determine the time periods, where the direct sound prevails and which can be used for directional evaluation, the auditory system analyzes loudness changes in different critical bands and also the stability of the perceived direction.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] If there is a strong attack of the loudness in several critical bands and if the perceived direction is stable, this attack is in all probability caused by the direct sound of a sound source, which is entering newly or which is changing its signal characteristics.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] This short time period is used by the auditory system for directional and loudness analysis of this sound.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] When reflections arrive a little bit later, they do not enhance the loudness inside the critical bands in such a strong way, but the directional cues become unstable, because there is a mix of sound of several reflection directions.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] As a result, no new directional analysis is triggered by the auditory system.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] This first detected direction from the direct sound is taken as the found sound source direction, until other strong loudness attacks, combined with stable directional information, indicate that a new directional analysis is possible.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] This kind of sound localization technique provides us the real virtual stereo system.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] It utilizes "smart" manikins, such as KEMAR, to glean signals or use DSP methods to simulate the transmission process from sources to ears.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] After amplifying, recording and transmitting, the two channels of received signals will be reproduced through earphones or speakers.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] This localization approach uses electroacoustic methods to obtain the spatial information of the original sound field by transferring the listener's auditory apparatus to the original sound field.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] The most considerable advantages of it would be that its acoustic images are lively and natural.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Also, it only needs two independent transmitted signals to reproduce the acoustic image of a 3D system.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] The representatives of this kind of system are SRS Audio Sandbox, Spatializer Audio Lab and Qsound Qxpander.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] They use HRTF to simulate the received acoustic signals at the ears from different directions with common binary-channel stereo reproduction.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Therefore, they can simulate reflected sound waves and improve subjective sense of space and envelopment.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Since they are para-virtualization stereo systems, the major goal of them is to simulate stereo sound information.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Traditional stereo systems use sensors that are quite different from human ears.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Although those sensors can receive the acoustic information from different directions, they do not have the same frequency response of human auditory system.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Therefore, when binary-channel mode is applied, human auditory systems still cannot feel the 3D sound effect field.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] However, the 3D para-virtualization stereo system overcome such disadvantages.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] It uses HRTF principles to glean acoustic information from the original sound field then produce a lively 3D sound field through common earphones or speakers.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Since the multichannel stereo systems require many reproduction channels, some researchers adopted the HRTF simulation technologies to reduce the number of reproduction channels.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] They use only two speakers to simulate multiple speakers in a multichannel system.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] This process is called as virtual reproduction.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Essentially, such approach uses both interaural difference principle and pinna filtering effect theory.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Unfortunately, this kind of approach cannot perfectly substitute the traditional multichannel stereo system, such as 5.1/7.1 surround sound system.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] That is because when the listening zone is relatively larger, simulation reproduction through HRTFs may cause invert acoustic images at symmetric positions.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Since most animals have two ears, many of the effects of the human auditory system can also be found in other animals.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Therefore, interaural time differences (interaural phase differences) and interaural level differences play a role for the hearing of many animals.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] But the influences on localization of these effects are dependent on head sizes, ear distances, the ear positions and the orientation of the ears.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Smaller animals like insects use different techniques as the separation of the ears are too small.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] For the process of animals emitting sound to improve localization, a biological form of active sonar, see animal echolocation.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] If the ears are located at the side of the head, similar lateral localization cues as for the human auditory system can be used.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] This means: evaluation of interaural time differences (interaural phase differences) for lower frequencies and evaluation of interaural level differences for higher frequencies.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] The evaluation of interaural phase differences is useful, as long as it gives unambiguous results.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] This is the case, as long as ear distance is smaller than half the length (maximal one wavelength) of the sound waves.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] For animals with a larger head than humans the evaluation range for interaural phase differences is shifted towards lower frequencies, for animals with a smaller head, this range is shifted towards higher frequencies.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] The lowest frequency which can be localized depends on the ear distance.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Animals with a greater ear distance can localize lower frequencies than humans can.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] For animals with a smaller ear distance the lowest localizable frequency is higher than for humans.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] If the ears are located at the side of the head, interaural level differences appear for higher frequencies and can be evaluated for localization tasks.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] For animals with ears at the top of the head, no shadowing by the head will appear and therefore there will be much less interaural level differences which could be evaluated.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Many of these animals can move their ears, and these ear movements can be used as a lateral localization cue.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] For many mammals there are also pronounced structures in the pinna near the entry of the ear canal.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] As a consequence, direction-dependent resonances can appear, which could be used as an additional localization cue, similar to the localization in the median plane in the human auditory system.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] There are additional localization cues which are also used by animals.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] For sound localization in the median plane (elevation of the sound) also two detectors can be used, which are positioned at different heights.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] In animals, however, rough elevation information is gained simply by tilting the head, provided that the sound lasts long enough to complete the movement.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] This explains the innate behavior of cocking the head to one side when trying to localize a sound precisely.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] To get instantaneous localization in more than two dimensions from time-difference or amplitude-difference cues requires more than two detectors.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] The tiny parasitic fly *Ormia ochracea* has become a model organism in sound localization experiments because of its unique ear.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] The animal is too small for the time difference of sound arriving at the two ears to be calculated in the usual way, yet it can determine the direction of sound sources with exquisite precision.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] The tympanic membranes of opposite ears are directly connected mechanically, allowing resolution of sub-microsecond time differences and requiring a new neural coding strategy.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Ho showed that the coupled-eardrum system in frogs can produce increased interaural vibration disparities when only small arrival time and sound level differences were available to the animal's head.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Efforts to build directional microphones based on the coupled-eardrum structure are underway.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Most owls are nocturnal or crepuscular birds of prey.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Because they hunt at night, they must rely on non-visual senses.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Experiments by Roger Payne have shown that owls are sensitive to the sounds made by their prey, not the heat or the smell.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] In fact, the sound cues are both necessary and sufficient for localization of mice from a distant location where they are perched.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] For this to work, the owls must be able to accurately localize both the azimuth and the elevation of the sound source.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Dolphins (and other odontocetes) rely on echolocation to aid in detecting, identifying, localizing, and capturing prey.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Dolphins can localize sounds both passively and actively (echolocation) with a resolution of about 1 deg.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Cross-modal matching (between vision and echolocation) suggests dolphins perceive the spatial structure of complex objects interrogated through echolocation, a feat that likely requires spatially resolving individual object features and integration into a holistic representation of object shape.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Although dolphins are sensitive to small, binaural intensity and time differences, mounting evidence suggests dolphins employ position-dependent spectral cues derived from well-developed head-related transfer functions, for sound localization in both the horizontal and vertical planes.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] A very small temporal integration time (264 μs) allows localization of multiple targets at varying distances.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Localization adaptations include pronounced asymmetry of the skull, nasal sacks, and specialized lipid structures in the forehead and jaws, as well as acoustically isolated middle and inner ears.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] The term 'binaural' literally signifies 'to hear with two ears', and was introduced in 1859 to signify the practice of listening to the same sound through both ears, or to two discrete sounds, one through each ear.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] It was not until 1916 that Carl Stumpf (1848–1936), a German philosopher and psychologist, distinguished between dichotic listening, which refers to the stimulation of each ear with a different stimulus, and diotic listening, the simultaneous stimulation of both ears with the same stimulus.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Later, it would become apparent that binaural hearing, whether dichotic or diotic, is the means by which sound localization occurs.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Scientific consideration of binaural hearing began before the phenomenon was so named, with speculations published in 1792 by William Charles Wells (1757–1817) based on his research into binocular vision.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Giovanni Battista Venturi (1746–1822) conducted and described experiments in which people tried to localize a sound using both ears, or one ear blocked with a finger.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] This work was not followed up on, and was only recovered after others had worked out how human sound localization works.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Lord Rayleigh (1842–1919) would do these same experiments and come to the results, without knowing Venturi had first done them, almost seventy-five years later.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Charles Wheatstone (1802–1875) did work on optics and color mixing, and also explored hearing.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] He invented a device he called a "microphone" that involved a metal plate over each ear, each connected to metal rods; he used this device to amplify sound.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] He also did experiments holding tuning forks to both ears at the same time, or separately, trying to work out how sense of hearing works, that he published in 1827.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Ernst Heinrich Weber (1795–1878) and August Seebeck (1805–1849) and William Charles Wells also attempted to compare and contrast what would become known as binaural hearing with the principles of binocular integration generally.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Understanding how the differences in sound signals between two ears contributes to auditory processing in such a way as to enable sound localization and direction was considerably advanced after the invention of the stethophone by Somerville Scott Alison in 1859, who coined the term 'binaural'.
[src:ambisonics/sound-localization] Alison based the stethophone on the stethoscope, which had been invented by René Théophile Hyacinthe Laennec (1781–1826); the stethophone had two separate "pickups", allowing the user to hear and compare sounds derived from two discrete locations.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] In mathematics and physical science, **spherical harmonics** are special functions defined on the surface of a sphere.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] They are often employed in solving partial differential equations in many scientific fields.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The table of spherical harmonics contains a list of common spherical harmonics.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Since the spherical harmonics form a complete set of orthogonal functions and thus an orthonormal basis, certain functions defined on the surface of a sphere can be written as a sum of these spherical harmonics.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] This is similar to periodic functions defined on a circle that can be expressed as a sum of circular functions (sines and cosines) via Fourier series.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Like the sines and cosines in Fourier series, the spherical harmonics may be organized by (spatial) angular frequency, as seen in the rows of functions in the illustration on the right.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Further, spherical harmonics are basis functions for irreducible representations of SO(3), the group of rotations in three dimensions, and thus play a central role in the group theoretic discussion of SO(3).
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Spherical harmonics originate from solving Laplace's equation in the spherical domains.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Functions that are solutions to Laplace's equation are called harmonics.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Despite their name, spherical harmonics take their simplest form in Cartesian coordinates, where they can be defined as homogeneous polynomials of degree $\ell$ in $(x,y,z)$ that obey Laplace's equation.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] In this setting, they may be viewed as the angular portion of a set of solutions to Laplace's equation in three dimensions, and this viewpoint is often taken as an alternative definition.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Spherical harmonics, as functions on the sphere, are eigenfunctions of the Laplace-Beltrami operator (see Higher dimensions).
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] A specific set of spherical harmonics, denoted $Y_{\ell }^{m}(\theta ,\varphi )$ or $Y_{\ell }^{m}({\mathbf {r} })$ , are known as Laplace's spherical harmonics, as they were first introduced by Pierre Simon de Laplace in 1782.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] These functions form an orthogonal system, and are thus basic to the expansion of a general function on the sphere as alluded to above.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] In 3D computer graphics, spherical harmonics play a role in a wide variety of topics including indirect lighting (ambient occlusion, global illumination, precomputed radiance transfer, etc.) and modelling of 3D shapes.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Spherical harmonics were first investigated in connection with the Newtonian potential of Newton's law of universal gravitation in three dimensions.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Each term in the above summation is an individual Newtonian potential for a point mass.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Just prior to that time, Adrien-Marie Legendre had investigated the expansion of the Newtonian potential in powers of *r* = |**x**| and *r*1 = |**x**1|.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] where *γ* is the angle between the vectors **x** and **x**1.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The functions $P_{i}:[-1,1]\to \mathbb {R}$ are the Legendre polynomials, and they can be derived as a special case of spherical harmonics.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Subsequently, in his 1782 memoir, Laplace investigated these coefficients using spherical coordinates to represent the angle *γ* between **x**1 and **x**.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] In 1867, William Thomson (Lord Kelvin) and Peter Guthrie Tait introduced the solid spherical harmonics in their *Treatise on Natural Philosophy*, and also first introduced the name of "spherical harmonics" for these functions.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The 19th century development of Fourier series made possible the solution of a wide variety of physical problems in rectangular domains, such as the solution of the heat equation and wave equation.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] This could be achieved by expansion of functions in series of trigonometric functions.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Whereas the trigonometric functions in a Fourier series represent the fundamental modes of vibration in a string, the spherical harmonics represent the fundamental modes of vibration of a sphere in much the same way.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Many aspects of the theory of Fourier series could be generalized by taking expansions in spherical harmonics rather than trigonometric functions.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Moreover, analogous to how trigonometric functions can equivalently be written as complex exponentials, spherical harmonics also possessed an equivalent form as complex-valued functions.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] This was a boon for problems possessing spherical symmetry, such as those of celestial mechanics originally studied by Laplace and Legendre.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The prevalence of spherical harmonics already in physics set the stage for their later importance in the 20th century birth of quantum mechanics.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The (complex-valued) spherical harmonics $S^{2}\to \mathbb {C}$ are eigenfunctions of the square of the orbital angular momentum operator $-i\hbar \mathbf {r} \times \nabla ,$ and therefore they represent the different quantized configurations of atomic orbitals.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Laplace's equation imposes that the Laplacian of a scalar field *f* is zero.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] A priori, *m* is a complex constant, but because Φ must be a periodic function whose period evenly divides 2*π*, *m* is necessarily an integer and Φ is a linear combination of the complex exponentials *e*± *imφ*.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The solution function *Y*(*θ*, *φ*) is regular at the poles of the sphere, where *θ* = 0, *π*.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Furthermore, a change of variables *t* = cos *θ* transforms this equation into the Legendre equation, whose solution is a multiple of the associated Legendre polynomial *Pm ℓ*(cos *θ*) .
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Finally, the equation for *R* has solutions of the form *R*(*r*) = *A rℓ* + *B r*−*ℓ* − 1; requiring the solution to be regular throughout **R**3 forces *B* = 0.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Here the solution was assumed to have the special form *Y*(*θ*, *φ*) = Θ(*θ*) Φ(*φ*).
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] For a given value of *ℓ*, there are 2*ℓ* + 1 independent solutions of this form, one for each integer *m* with −*ℓ* ≤ *m* ≤ *ℓ*.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Here $Y_{\ell }^{m}:S^{2}\to \mathbb {C}$ is called a **spherical harmonic function of degree *ℓ* and order *m***, $P_{\ell }^{m}:[-1,1]\to \mathbb {R}$ is an associated Legendre polynomial, *N* is a normalization constant, and *θ* and *φ* represent colatitude and longitude, respectively.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] In particular, the colatitude *θ*, or polar angle, ranges from *0* at the North Pole, to *π*/2 at the Equator, to *π* at the South Pole, and the longitude *φ*, or azimuth, may assume all values with 0 ≤ *φ* < 2*π*.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] In fact, for any such solution, *rℓ Y*(*θ*, *φ*) is the expression in spherical coordinates of a homogeneous polynomial $\mathbb {R} ^{3}\to \mathbb {C}$ that is harmonic (see below), and so counting dimensions shows that there are 2*ℓ* + 1 linearly independent such polynomials.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] where the $f_{\ell }^{m}\in \mathbb {C}$ are constants and the factors *rℓ Yℓm* are known as (*regular*) solid harmonics $\mathbb {R} ^{3}\to \mathbb {C}$ .
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] For $r>R$ , the solid harmonics with negative powers of r (the *irregular* solid harmonics $\mathbb {R} ^{3}\setminus \{\mathbf {0} \}\to \mathbb {C}$ ) are chosen instead.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] In that case, one needs to expand the solution of known regions in Laurent series (about $r=\infty$ ), instead of the Taylor series (about $r=0$ ) used above, to match the terms and find series expansion coefficients $f_{\ell }^{m}\in \mathbb {C}$ .
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] If *Y* is a joint eigenfunction of **L**2 and *L**z*, then by definition ${\begin{aligned}\mathbf {L} ^{2}Y&=\lambda Y\\L_{z}Y&=mY\end{aligned}}$ for some real numbers *m* and *λ*.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Here *m* must in fact be an integer, for *Y* must be periodic in the coordinate *φ* with period a number that evenly divides 2*π*.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] In particular, *L**k* + : *E**λ*,*m* → *E**λ*,*m*+*k* must be zero for *k* sufficiently large, because the inequality *λ* ≥ *m*2 must hold in each of the nontrivial joint eigenspaces.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The foregoing has been all worked out in the spherical coordinate representation, $\langle \theta ,\varphi |lm\rangle =Y_{l}^{m}(\theta ,\varphi )$ but may be expressed more abstractly in the complete, orthonormal spherical ket basis.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The spherical harmonics can be expressed as the restriction to the unit sphere of certain polynomial functions $\mathbb {R} ^{3}\to \mathbb {C}$ .
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Specifically, we say that a (complex-valued) polynomial function $p:\mathbb {R} ^{3}\to \mathbb {C}$ is *homogeneous* of degree $\ell$ if $p(\lambda \mathbf {x} )=\lambda ^{\ell }p(\mathbf {x} )$ for all real numbers $\lambda \in \mathbb {R}$ and all $\mathbf {x} \in \mathbb {R} ^{3}$ .
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] We say that p is *harmonic* if $\Delta p=0,$ where $\Delta$ is the Laplacian.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] For example, when $\ell =1$ , $\mathbf {A} _{1}$ is just the 3-dimensional space of all linear functions $\mathbb {R} ^{3}\to \mathbb {C}$ , since any such function is automatically harmonic.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] For any $\ell$ , the space $\mathbf {H} _{\ell }$ of spherical harmonics of degree $\ell$ is just the space of restrictions to the sphere $S^{2}$ of the elements of $\mathbf {A} _{\ell }$ .
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] As suggested in the introduction, this perspective is presumably the origin of the term "spherical harmonic" (i.e., the restriction to the sphere of a harmonic function).
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] For example, for any $c\in \mathbb {C}$ the formula $p(x_{1},x_{2},x_{3})=c(x_{1}+ix_{2})^{\ell }$ defines a homogeneous polynomial of degree $\ell$ with domain and codomain $\mathbb {R} ^{3}\to \mathbb {C}$ , which happens to be independent of $x_{3}$ .
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] This polynomial is easily seen to be harmonic.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] One source of confusion with the definition of the spherical harmonic functions concerns a phase factor of $(-1)^{m}$ , commonly referred to as the Condon–Shortley phase in the quantum mechanical literature.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] This phase factor may be included either in the definition of the associated Legendre polynomials or in the definition of the spherical harmonic functions, but it should not be counted twice.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Some authors instead define associated Legendre functions without this phase factor.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] There is no requirement to use the Condon–Shortley phase in the definition of the spherical harmonic functions, but including it can simplify some quantum mechanical operations, especially the application of raising and lowering operators.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The geodesy and magnetics communities commonly use conventions in which the Condon–Shortley phase factor is not included in the associated Legendre functions or in the spherical harmonics.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Several different normalizations are in common use for the Laplace spherical harmonic functions $S^{2}\to \mathbb {C}$ .
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] These normalization choices are independent of the placement of the Condon–Shortley phase.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The disciplines of geodesy and spectral analysis often use the corresponding $4\pi$ -normalized harmonics.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The magnetics community, in contrast, often uses Schmidt semi-normalized harmonics.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] For the phase convention used in this article, the complex spherical harmonics satisfy $Y_{\ell }^{m}{}^{*}(\theta ,\varphi )=(-1)^{m}Y_{\ell }^{-m}(\theta ,\varphi ),$ where the superscript * denotes complex conjugation.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] This equation also follows from the relation of the spherical harmonic functions with the Wigner D-matrix.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The real spherical harmonics $Y_{\ell m}:S^{2}\to \mathbb {R}$ are sometimes known as *tesseral spherical harmonics*.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] These functions have the same orthonormality properties as the complex ones $Y_{\ell }^{m}:S^{2}\to \mathbb {C}$ above.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The real spherical harmonics $Y_{\ell m}$ with *m* > 0 are said to be of cosine type, and those with *m* < 0 of sine type.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] With a different placement of that phase, the displayed signs must be changed consistently.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The same sine and cosine factors can be also seen in the following subsection that deals with the Cartesian representation.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] See here for a list of real spherical harmonics up to and including $\ell =4$ , which can be seen to be consistent with the output of the equations above.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] From the analytic solutions for the hydrogen atom, the eigenfunctions of the angular part of the wave function are spherical harmonics.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] However, the solutions of the non-relativistic Schrödinger equation without magnetic terms can be made real.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] This is why the real forms are extensively used in basis functions for quantum chemistry, as the programs do not then need to use complex algebra.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Here, the real functions span the same space as the complex ones would.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] For example, as can be seen from the table of spherical harmonics, the usual *p* functions ( $\ell =1$ ) are complex and mix axis directions, but the real versions are essentially just *x*, *y*, and *z*.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] More specifically, it is the (unique up to normalization) Gelfand-Tsetlin-basis of this representation of the rotational group $SO(3)$ and an explicit formula for $R_{\ell }^{m}$ in cartesian coordinates can be derived from that fact.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] It suffices to take v and $\lambda$ as real parameters.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] In naming this generating function after Herglotz, we follow Courant & Hilbert 1962, §VII.7, who credit unpublished notes by him for its discovery.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Essentially all the properties of the spherical harmonics can be derived from this generating function.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] They are, moreover, a standardized set with a fixed scale or normalization.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The factor ${\bar {\Pi }}_{\ell }^{m}(z)$ is essentially the associated Legendre polynomial $P_{\ell }^{m}(\cos \theta )$ , and the factors $(A_{m}\pm iB_{m})$ are essentially $e^{\pm im\varphi }$ .
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The spherical harmonics have deep and consequential properties under the operations of spatial inversion (parity) and rotation.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The spherical harmonics have definite parity.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] That is, they are either even or odd with respect to inversion about the origin.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Inversion is represented by the operator $P\Psi (\mathbf {r} )=\Psi (-\mathbf {r} )$ .
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] In terms of the spherical angles, parity transforms a point with coordinates $\{\theta ,\varphi \}$ to $\{\pi -\theta ,\pi +\varphi \}$ .
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Parity continues to hold for real spherical harmonics, and for spherical harmonics in higher dimensions: applying a point reflection to a spherical harmonic of degree ℓ changes the sign by a factor of (−1)*ℓ*.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Consider a rotation ${\mathcal {R}}$ about the origin that sends the unit vector $\mathbf {r}$ to $\mathbf {r} '$ .
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Under this operation, a spherical harmonic of degree $\ell$ and order m transforms into a linear combination of spherical harmonics of the same degree.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] However, this is not the standard way of expressing this property.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The rotational behavior of the spherical harmonics is perhaps their quintessential feature from the viewpoint of group theory.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The $Y_{\ell }^{m}$ 's of degree $\ell$ provide a basis set of functions for the irreducible representation of the group SO(3) of dimension $(2\ell +1)$ .
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Many facts about spherical harmonics (such as the addition theorem) that are proved laboriously using the methods of analysis acquire simpler proofs and deeper significance using the methods of symmetry.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The Laplace spherical harmonics $Y_{\ell }^{m}:S^{2}\to \mathbb {C}$ form a complete set of orthonormal functions and thus form an orthonormal basis of the Hilbert space of square-integrable functions $L_{\mathbb {C} }^{2}(S^{2})$ .
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The expansion coefficients are the analogs of Fourier coefficients, and can be obtained by multiplying the above equation by the complex conjugate of a spherical harmonic, integrating over the solid angle Ω, and utilizing the above orthogonality relationships.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] This is justified rigorously by basic Hilbert space theory.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] If the coefficients decay in *ℓ* sufficiently rapidly — for instance, exponentially — then the series also converges uniformly to *f*.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The convergence of the series holds again in the same sense, namely the real spherical harmonics $Y_{\ell m}:S^{2}\to \mathbb {R}$ form a complete set of orthonormal functions and thus form an orthonormal basis of the Hilbert space of square-integrable functions $L_{\mathbb {R} }^{2}(S^{2})$ .
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The completeness relation is a distributional equality between a sum over all indices and the Dirac delta function.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] For the spherical harmonics, the Dirac delta is the tensor product of two Dirac delta functions, one for the azimuthal angle on the sphere, and one for the polar angle.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The total power of a function *f* is defined in the signal processing literature as the integral of the function squared, divided by the area of its domain.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] is defined as the angular power spectrum (for Schmidt semi-normalized harmonics).
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] If the functions *f* and *g* have a zero mean (i.e., the spectral coefficients *f*00 and *g*00 are zero), then *S**ff*(*ℓ*) and *S**fg*(*ℓ*) represent the contributions to the function's variance and covariance for degree ℓ, respectively.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] When *β* = 0, the spectrum is "white" as each degree possesses equal power.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] When *β* < 0, the spectrum is termed "red" as there is more power at the low degrees with long wavelengths than higher degrees.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Finally, when *β* > 0, the spectrum is termed "blue".
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The condition on the order of growth of *S**ff*(*ℓ*) is related to the order of differentiability of *f* in the next section.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Spherical harmonics are used to approximate functions on the sphere, and the order of decay of the power governs smoothness.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Let $\Pi _{n}(S^{2})$ denote the space spanned by spherical harmonics of degree at most n .
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] with the norm taken in $L^{p}(S^{2})$ , or in the uniform norm when $p=\infty$ .
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The asymptotic behavior of $E_{n}(f)_{p}$ as $n\to \infty$ gives a quantitative measure of how well f can be approximated by low-degree spherical harmonics.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] This is analogous to approximation by trigonometric polynomials in ordinary Fourier analysis.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] On the circle, smoothness can be measured by the decay of Fourier coefficients.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] On the sphere, smoother functions admit faster approximation by spherical polynomials, while conversely, sufficiently rapid decay of the approximation error implies smoothness.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] More precisely, Sobolev-type smoothness can also be described spectrally, since spherical harmonics of degree $\ell$ are eigenfunctions of the Laplace–Beltrami operator with eigenvalue $-\ell (\ell +1)$ .
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] For $p=2$ this relation can be stated especially explicitly.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Thus $f\in H^{s}(S^{2})$ precisely when this weighted sum is finite.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Since $\ell (\ell +1)$ grows like $\ell ^{2}$ , higher Sobolev smoothness requires faster decay of the power in high degrees.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] which bounds the approximation error by the Sobolev norm.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] With the above power normalization, a decay estimate of the form $S_{ff}(\ell )=O(\ell ^{-\alpha })$ implies membership in $H^{s}(S^{2})$ whenever $\alpha >2s+1$ .
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Thus sufficiently fast polynomial decay of the power spectrum implies differentiability, and decay faster than every power implies smoothness of all orders.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] A mathematical result of considerable interest and use is called the *addition theorem* for spherical harmonics.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] where *P**ℓ* is the Legendre polynomial of degree ℓ.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] This expression is valid for both real and complex harmonics.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] The result can be proven analytically, using the properties of the Poisson kernel in the unit ball, or geometrically by applying a rotation to the vector **y** so that it points along the *z*-axis, and then directly calculating the right-hand side.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] In the expansion (**1**), the left-hand side $P_{\ell }(\mathbf {x} \cdot \mathbf {y} )$ is a constant multiple of the degree ℓ zonal spherical harmonic.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] From this perspective, one has the following generalization to higher dimensions.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] Let *Y**j* be an arbitrary orthonormal basis of the space **H***ℓ* of degree ℓ spherical harmonics on the n-sphere.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] Combining (**2**) and (**3**) gives (**1**) in dimension *n* = 2 when **x** and **y** are represented in spherical coordinates.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] The values of c and $\gamma$ that result in non-zero terms in this sum are determined by the selection rules for the 3j-symbols.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] The Clebsch–Gordan coefficients are the coefficients appearing in the expansion of the product of two spherical harmonics in terms of spherical harmonics themselves.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] A variety of techniques are available for doing essentially the same calculation, including the Wigner 3-jm symbol, the Racah coefficients, and the Slater integrals.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] Abstractly, the Clebsch–Gordan coefficients express the tensor product of two irreducible representations of the rotation group as a sum of irreducible representations: suitably normalized, the coefficients are then the multiplicities.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] The Laplace spherical harmonics $Y_{\ell }^{m}$ can be visualized by considering their "nodal lines", that is, the set of points on the sphere where $\Re [Y_{\ell }^{m}]=0$ , or alternatively where $\Im [Y_{\ell }^{m}]=0$ .
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] Nodal lines of $Y_{\ell }^{m}$ are composed of *ℓ* circles: there are |*m*| circles along longitudes and *ℓ*−|*m*| circles along latitudes.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] One can determine the number of nodal lines of each type by counting the number of zeros of $Y_{\ell }^{m}$ in the $\theta$ and $\varphi$ directions respectively.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] Considering $Y_{\ell }^{m}$ as a function of $\theta$ , the real and imaginary components of the associated Legendre polynomials each possess *ℓ*−|*m*| zeros, each giving rise to a nodal 'line of latitude'.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] On the other hand, considering $Y_{\ell }^{m}$ as a function of $\varphi$ , the trigonometric sin and cos functions possess 2|*m*| zeros, each of which gives rise to a nodal 'line of longitude'.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] When the spherical harmonic order *m* is zero (upper-left in the figure), the spherical harmonic functions do not depend upon longitude, and are referred to as ***zonal***.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] Such spherical harmonics are a special case of zonal spherical functions.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] When *ℓ* = |*m*| (bottom-right in the figure), there are no zero crossings in latitude, and the functions are referred to as ***sectoral***.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] For the other cases, the functions checker the sphere, and they are referred to as ***tesseral***.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] More general spherical harmonics of degree ℓ are not necessarily those of the Laplace basis $Y_{\ell }^{m}$ , and their nodal sets can be of a fairly general kind.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] The classical spherical harmonics are defined as complex-valued functions on the unit sphere $S^{2}$ inside three-dimensional Euclidean space $\mathbb {R} ^{3}$ .
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] Spherical harmonics can be generalized to higher-dimensional Euclidean space $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ as follows, leading to functions $S^{n-1}\to \mathbb {C}$ .
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] Let **P***ℓ* denote the space of complex-valued homogeneous polynomials of degree ℓ in n real variables, here considered as functions $\mathbb {R} ^{n}\to \mathbb {C}$ .
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] Let **A***ℓ* denote the subspace of **P***ℓ* consisting of all harmonic polynomials: $\mathbf {A} _{\ell }:=\{p\in \mathbf {P} _{\ell }\,\mid \,\Delta p=0\}\,.$ These are the (regular) solid spherical harmonics.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] The space **H***ℓ* of spherical harmonics of degree ℓ is a representation of the symmetry group of rotations around a point (SO(3)) and its double-cover SU(2).
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] Indeed, rotations act on the two-dimensional sphere, and thus also on **H***ℓ* by function composition $\psi \mapsto \psi \circ \rho ^{-1}$ for ψ a spherical harmonic and ρ a rotation.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] The representation **H***ℓ* is an irreducible representation of SO(3).
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] The elements of **H***ℓ* arise as the restrictions to the sphere of elements of **A***ℓ*: harmonic polynomials homogeneous of degree ℓ on three-dimensional Euclidean space **R**3.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] Thus as an irreducible representation of SO(3), **H***ℓ* is isomorphic to the space of traceless symmetric tensors of degree ℓ.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] More generally, the analogous statements hold in higher dimensions: the space **H***ℓ* of spherical harmonics on the n-sphere is the irreducible representation of SO(*n*+1) corresponding to the traceless symmetric ℓ-tensors.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] However, whereas every irreducible tensor representation of SO(2) and SO(3) is of this kind, the special orthogonal groups in higher dimensions have additional irreducible representations that do not arise in this manner.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] The special orthogonal groups have additional spin representations that are not tensor representations, and are *typically* not spherical harmonics.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] An exception are the spin representation of SO(3): strictly speaking these are representations of the double cover SU(2) of SO(3).
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] In turn, SU(2) is identified with the group of unit quaternions, and so coincides with the 3-sphere.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] The spaces of spherical harmonics on the 3-sphere are certain spin representations of SO(3), with respect to the action by quaternionic multiplication.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] Spherical harmonics can be separated into two sets of functions.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] One is hemispherical harmonics (HSH), orthogonal and complete on hemisphere.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] Another is complementary hemispherical harmonics (CHSH).
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] The angle-preserving symmetries of the two-sphere are described by the group of Möbius transformations PSL(2,**C**).
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] With respect to this group, the sphere is equivalent to the usual Riemann sphere.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] The group PSL(2,**C**) is isomorphic to the (proper) Lorentz group, and its action on the two-sphere agrees with the action of the Lorentz group on the celestial sphere in Minkowski space.
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] The analog of the spherical harmonics for the Lorentz group is given by the hypergeometric series; furthermore, the spherical harmonics can be re-expressed in terms of the hypergeometric series, as SO(3) = PSU(2) is a subgroup of PSL(2,**C**).
[src:ambisonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] More generally, hypergeometric series can be generalized to describe the symmetries of any symmetric space; in particular, hypergeometric series can be developed for any Lie group.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The technique enhances the perception of sound spatialization by exploiting sound localization: a listener's ability to identify the location or origin of a detected sound in direction and distance.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] This is achieved by using multiple discrete audio channels routed to an array of loudspeakers.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Surround sound typically has a listener location (sweet spot) where the audio effects work best and presents a fixed or forward perspective of the sound field to the listener at this location.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Surround sound formats vary in reproduction and recording methods, along with the number and positioning of additional channels.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The most common surround sound specification, the ITU's 5.1 standard, calls for 6 speakers: center (C), in front of the listener; left (L) and right (R), at angles of 60°; left surround (LS) and right surround (RS) at angles of 100–120°; and a subwoofer, whose position is not critical.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Surround sound can benefit audio contents with large dynamic range, such as dramas, movies and games.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Though cinema and soundtracks represent the major uses of surround techniques, its scope of application is broader than that, as surround sound permits the creation of an audio environment for all sorts of purposes.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Multichannel audio techniques may be used to reproduce contents as varied as music, speech, natural or synthetic sounds for cinema, television, broadcasting, or computers.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] In terms of music content for example, a live performance may use multichannel techniques in the context of an open-air concert, of a musical theatre performance or for broadcasting; for a film, specific techniques are adapted to movie theater or to home (e.g. home cinema systems).
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The narrative space is also a content that can be enhanced through multichannel techniques.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] This applies mainly to cinema narratives, for example the speech of the characters of a film, but may also be applied to plays performed in a theatre, to a conference, or to integrate voice-based comments in an archeological site or monument.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] For example, an exhibition may be enhanced with topical ambient sound of water, birds, train or machine noise.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Topical natural sounds may also be used in educational applications.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Other fields of application include video game consoles, personal computers and other platforms.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] In such applications, the content would typically be synthetic noise produced by the computer device in interaction with its user.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Significant work has also been done using surround sound for enhanced situation awareness in military and public safety applications.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Commercial surround sound media include videocassettes, DVDs, and SDTV broadcasts encoded as analog matrixed Dolby Surround, compressed Dolby Digital, and DTS, and lossless audio such as DTS HD Master Audio and Dolby TrueHD on HDTV, Blu-ray Disc, and HD DVD, which are identical to the studio master.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Other commercial formats include the competing DVD-Audio (DVD-A) and Super Audio CD (SACD) formats, and MP3 Surround.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Cinema 5.1 surround formats include Dolby Digital and DTS.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Sony Dynamic Digital Sound (SDDS) is an 8-channel cinema configuration that features 5 independent audio channels across the front with two independent surround channels, and a Low-frequency effects channel.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Traditional 7.1 surround speaker configuration introduces two additional rear speakers to the conventional 5.1 arrangement, for a total of four surround channels and three front channels, to create a more 360° sound field.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Most surround sound recordings are created by film production companies or video game producers; however, some consumer camcorders have such capability either built-in or available separately.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Surround sound technologies can also be used in music to enable new methods of artistic expression.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] After the failure of quadraphonic audio in the 1970s, multichannel music has slowly been reintroduced since 1999 with the help of SACD and DVD-Audio formats.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Some AV receivers, stereophonic systems, and computer sound cards contain integral digital signal processors or digital audio processors to simulate surround sound from a stereophonic source (see fake stereo).
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] In 1967, the rock group Pink Floyd performed the first-ever surround sound concert at "Games for May", a lavish affair at London’s Queen Elizabeth Hall where the band debuted its custom-made quadraphonic speaker system.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The control device they had made, the Azimuth Co-ordinator, is now displayed at London's Victoria and Albert Museum, as part of their Theatre Collections gallery.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Netflix can support DRM-protected surround sound; but if TV set or audio device does not support Dolby-based DRM, it wall fallback to stereo audio.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The first documented use of surround sound was in 1940, for Disney's animated film *Fantasia*.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Walt Disney was inspired by Nikolai Rimsky-Korsakov's operatic piece *Flight of the Bumblebee* to have a bumblebee featured in his musical *Fantasia* and also sound as if it was flying in all parts of the theatre.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The initial multichannel audio application was called 'Fantasound', comprising three audio channels and speakers.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The sound was diffused throughout the cinema, controlled by an engineer using some 54 loudspeakers.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The surround sound was achieved using the sum and the difference of the phase of the sound.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] However, this experimental use of surround sound was excluded from the film in later showings.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] In 1952, surround sound successfully reappeared with the film "This is Cinerama", using discrete seven-channel sound, and the race to develop other surround sound methods took off.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] For the release of the 1953 20th Century Fox film *The Robe*, the studio felt the film needed a larger soundstage to match its wider CinemaScope presentation and released it with four-track magnetic stereo sound with left, right, center and mono surround channels.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Edgar Varese's Poème électronique, created for the Iannis Xenakis-designed Philips Pavilion at the 1958 Brussels World's Fair, also used spatial audio with 425 loudspeakers used to move sound throughout the pavilion.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Sound designers commonly regard this as the origin of the (now standard) concept of surround sound.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The program was popular, and Jacobs and Belson were invited to reproduce it at the 1958 World Expo in Brussels.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] There are also many other composers who created ground-breaking surround sound works in the same time period.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] In 1978, a concept devised by Max Bell for Dolby Laboratories called *split surround* was tested with the movie *Superman*.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] This led to the 70mm stereo surround release of *Apocalypse Now*, which became one of the first formal releases in cinemas with three channels in the front and two in the rear.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] There were typically five speakers behind the screens of 70mm-capable cinemas, but only the left, center and right were used full-frequency, while center-left and center-right were only used for bass-frequencies (as it is currently common).
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The *Apocalypse Now* encoder/decoder was designed by Michael Karagosian, also for Dolby Laboratories.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The surround mix was produced by an Oscar-winning crew led by Walter Murch for American Zoetrope.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The format was also deployed in 1982 with the stereo surround release of *Blade Runner*.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The 5.1 version of surround sound originated in 1987 at the famous French Cabaret Moulin Rouge.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] A French engineer, Dominique Bertrand, used a mixing board specially designed in cooperation with Solid State Logic, based on the 5000 series and including six channels.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Respectively: A left, B right, C center, D left rear, E right rear, F bass.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The same engineer had already achieved a 3.1 system in 1974, for the International Summit of Francophone States in Dakar, Senegal.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Surround sound is created in several ways.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] A second approach is processing the audio with psychoacoustic sound localization methods to simulate a two-dimensional (2-D) sound field with headphones.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] A third approach, based on Huygens' principle, attempts to reconstruct the recorded sound field wavefronts within the listening space; an *audio hologram* form.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] One form, wave field synthesis (WFS), produces a sound field with an even error field over the entire area.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Commercial WFS systems, currently marketed by companies *sonic emotion* and *Iosono*, require many loudspeakers and significant computing power.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The 4th approach is using three mics, one for front, one for side and one for rear, also called Double MS recording.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The Ambisonics form, also based on Huygens' principle, gives an exact sound reconstruction at the central point; however, it is less accurate away from the central point.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] There are many free and commercial software programs available for Ambisonics, which dominates most of the consumer market, especially musicians using electronic and computer music.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Moreover, Ambisonics products are the standard in surround sound hardware sold by Meridian Audio.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] In its simplest form, Ambisonics consumes few resources, however this is not true for recent developments, such as Near Field Compensated Higher Order Ambisonics.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Some years ago it was shown that, in the limit, WFS and Ambisonics converge.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] However, there are more ways to create surround sound out of stereo, for instance, with the routines based on stereophonic sound audio source input or audio source file to quadraphonic sound audio playback, where instruments were divided over 4 speakers in the studio.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] This way of creating surround with software or firmware routines is normally referred to as *upmixing*, which was particularly successful on the Sansui QSD-series decoders that had a mode where it mapped the L ↔ R stereo onto an ∩ arc.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] This is a compromise between the ideal image creation of a room and that of practicality and compatibility with two-channel stereo.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Because most surround sound mixes are produced for 5.1 surround (6 channels), larger setups require matrixes or processors to feed the additional speakers.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The standard surround setup consists of three front speakers LCR (left, center and right), two surround speakers LS and RS (left and right surround respectively) and a subwoofer for the low-frequency effects (LFE) channel, which is low-pass filtered at 120 Hz.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The Surround channels are placed 100–120 degrees from the center channel, with the subwoofer's positioning not being critical due to the low directional factor of frequencies below 120 Hz.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The ITU standard also allows for additional surround speakers, which need to be distributed evenly between 60 and 150 degrees.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Surround mixes of more or fewer channels are acceptable, if they are compatible, as described by the ITU-R BS.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The 3-1 channel setup (consisting of one monophonic surround channel) is such a case, where both LS and RS are fed by the monophonic signal at an attenuated level of -3 dB.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The function of the center channel is to anchor the signal so that any central panned images do not shift when a listener is moving or is sitting away from the sweet spot.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The center channel also prevents any timbral modifications from occurring, which is typical for 2-channel stereo, due to phase differences at the two ears of a listener.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The center channel is especially used in films and television, with dialogue primarily feeding the center channel.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The function of the center channel can either be of a monophonic nature (as with dialogue) or it can be used in combination with the left and right channels for true three-channel stereo.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Motion Pictures tend to use the center channel for monophonic purposes with stereo being reserved purely for the left and right channels.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Surround microphone techniques have, however, been developed that fully use the potential of three-channel stereo.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] In 5.1 surround, phantom images between the front speakers are quite accurate, with images towards the back and especially to the sides being unstable.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The localization of a virtual source, based on level differences between two loudspeakers to the side of a listener, shows great inconsistency across the standardized 5.1 setup, also being largely affected by movement away from the reference position.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] 7.1 channel surround is another setup, most commonly used in large cinemas, that is compatible with 5.1 surround, though it is not stated in the ITU standards.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] 7.1 channel surround adds two additional channels, center-left (CL) and center-right (CR) to the 5.1 surround setup, with the speakers situated 15 degrees off center from the listener.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] This convention is used to cover an increased angle between the front loudspeakers as a product of a larger screen.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Most 2-channel stereophonic microphone techniques are compatible with a 3-channel setup (LCR), as many of these techniques already contain a center microphone or microphone pair.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Microphone techniques for LCR should, however, try to obtain greater channel separation to prevent conflicting phantom images between L/C and L/R, for example.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Specialised techniques have therefore been developed for 3-channel stereo.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Surround microphone techniques largely depend on the setup used, therefore being biased towards the 5.1 surround setup, as this is the standard.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Surround recording techniques can be differentiated into those that use single arrays of microphones placed in close proximity and those treating front and rear channels with separate arrays.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Close arrays present more accurate phantom images, whereas separate treatment of rear channels is usually used for ambiance.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] For accurate depiction of an acoustic environment, such as a halls, side reflections are essential.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Appropriate microphone techniques should therefore be used if the room impression is important.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Although the reproduction of side images is very unstable in the 5.1 surround setup, room impressions can still be accurately presented.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Some microphone techniques used for coverage of three front channels, include double-stereo techniques, INA-3 (Ideal Cardioid Arrangement), the Decca tree setup and the OCT (Optimum Cardioid Triangle).
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Surround techniques are largely based on 3-channel techniques with additional microphones used for the surround channels.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] A distinguishing factor for the pickup of the front channels in surround is that less reverberation should be picked up, as the surround microphones will be responsible for the pickup of reverberation.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Cardioid, hypercardioid, or supercardioid polar patterns will therefore often replace omnidirectional polar patterns for surround recordings.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] To compensate for the lost low-end of directional (pressure gradient) microphones, additional omnidirectional (pressure microphones), exhibiting an extended low-end response, can be added.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The microphone's output is usually low-pass filtered.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] A simple surround microphone configuration involves the use of a front array in combination with two backward-facing omnidirectional room microphones placed about 10–15 meters away from the front array.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] If echoes are notable, the front array can be delayed appropriately.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Alternatively, backward-facing cardioid microphones can be placed closer to the front array for a similar reverberation pickup.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The INA-5 (Ideal Cardioid Arrangement) is a surround microphone array that uses five cardioid microphones resembling the angles of the standardized surround loudspeaker configuration defined by the ITU Rec.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Dimensions between the front three microphone as well as the polar patterns of the microphones can be changed for different pickup angles and ambient response.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] This technique therefore allows for great flexibility.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] A well-established microphone array is the Fukada Tree, which is a modified variant of the Decca Tree stereo technique.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The array consists of five spaced cardioid microphones, three front microphones resembling a Decca Tree and two surround microphones.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Two additional omnidirectional outriggers can be added to enlarge the perceived size of the orchestra or to better integrate the front and surround channels.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The L, R, LS and RS microphones should be placed in a square formation, with L/R and LS/RS angled at 45 degrees and 135 degrees from the center microphone, respectively.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Spacing between these microphones should be about 1.8 meters.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] This square formation is responsible for the room impressions.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The center channel is placed a meter in front of the L and R channels, producing a strong center image.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The surround microphones are usually placed at the critical distance (where the direct and reverberant field is equal), with the full array usually situated several meters above and behind the conductor.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The NHK (Japanese broadcasting company) developed an alternative technique also involving five cardioid microphones.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Here, a baffle is used for separation between the front left and right channels, which are 30 cm apart.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Outrigger omnidirectional microphones, low-pass filtered at 250 Hz, are spaced 3 meters apart in line with the L and R cardioids.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] These compensate for the bass roll-off of the cardioid microphones and also add expansiveness.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] A 3-meter spaced microphone pair, situated 2–3 meters behind the front array, is used for the surround channels.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The center channel is again placed slightly forward, with the L/R and LS/RS again angled at 45 and 135 degrees, respectively.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The OCT-Surround (Optimum Cardioid Triangle-Surround) microphone array is an augmented technique of the stereo OCT technique using the same front array with added surround microphones.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The front array is designed for minimum crosstalk, with the front left and right microphones having supercardioid polar patterns and angled at 90 degrees relative to the center microphone.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] It is important that high-quality small diaphragm microphones are used for the L and R channels to reduce off-axis coloration.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Equalization can also be used to flatten the response of the supercardioid microphones to signals coming in at up to about 30 degrees from the front of the array.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The center channel is placed slightly forward.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The surround microphones are backward-facing cardioid microphones that are placed 40 cm back from the L and R microphones.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The L, R, LS and RS microphones pick up early reflections from both the sides and the back of an acoustic venue, therefore giving significant room impressions.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Spacing between the L and R microphones can be varied to obtain the required stereo width.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Specialized microphone arrays have been developed to record a space's ambiance.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] These arrays are used in combination with suitable front arrays or can be added to above-mentioned surround techniques.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The Hamasaki square (also proposed by NHK) is a well-established microphone array used for the pickup of hall ambience.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Four figure-eight microphones are arranged in a square, ideally placed far away and high up in the hall.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Spacing between the microphones should be between 1–3 meters.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Another ambient technique is the IRT (Institut für Rundfunktechnik) cross.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Here, four cardioid microphones, 90 degrees relative to one another, are placed in a square formation, separated by 21–25 cm.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The front two microphones should be positioned 45 degrees off axis from the sound source.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] This technique therefore, resembles back-to-back near-coincident stereo pairs.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The microphone outputs are fed to the L, R and LS, RS channels.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The disadvantage of this approach is that direct sound pickup is quite significant.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Many recordings do not require pickup of side reflections.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] For Live Pop music concerts, a more appropriate array for the pickup of ambiance is the cardioid trapezium.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] All four cardioid microphones are backward facing and angled at 60 degrees from one another, therefore similar to a semi-circle.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] This is effective for the pickup of the audience and ambiance.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] All the above-mentioned microphone arrays take up considerable space, making them quite ineffective for field recordings.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] In this respect, the double mid-side (MS) technique is quite advantageous.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] This array uses back-to-back cardioid microphones, one facing forward, the other backward, combined with either one or two figure-eight microphones.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Different channels are obtained by the sum and difference of the figure-eight and cardioid patterns.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] When using only one figure-eight microphone, the double MS technique is extremely compact and therefore also perfectly compatible with monophonic playback.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] This technique also allows for postproduction changes of the pickup angle.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] There is a notation difference before and after the bass management system.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Before the bass management system, there is an LFE channel.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] After the bass management system, there is a subwoofer signal.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] A common misunderstanding is the belief that the LFE channel is the *subwoofer channel*.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The bass management system may direct bass to one or more subwoofers (if present) from *any* channel, not just from the LFE channel.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Also, if there is no subwoofer speaker present, then the bass management system can direct the LFE channel to one or more of the main speakers.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Because the LFE channel requires only a fraction of the bandwidth of the other audio channels, it is referred to as the *.1* channel; for example *5.1* or *7.1*.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The LFE channel is a source of some confusion in surround sound.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] It was originally developed to carry extremely low *sub-bass* cinematic sound effects (e.g., the loud rumble of thunder or explosions) on their own channel.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] This allowed theaters to control the volume of these effects to suit the particular cinema's acoustic environment and sound reproduction system.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Independent control of the sub-bass effects also reduced the problem of intermodulation distortion in analog movie sound reproduction.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] In the original movie theater implementation, the LFE was a separate channel fed to one or more subwoofers.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Home replay systems, however, may not have a separate subwoofer, so modern home surround decoders and systems often include a bass management system that allows bass on any channel (main or LFE) to be fed only to the loudspeakers that can handle low-frequency signals.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The salient point here is that the LFE channel is not the *subwoofer channel*; there may be no subwoofer and, if there is, it may be handling a good deal more than effects.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Some record labels such as Telarc and Chesky have argued that LFE channels are not needed in a modern digital multichannel entertainment system.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] They argue that, given loudspeakers that have low-frequency response to 30 Hz, all available channels have a full-frequency range and, as such, there is no need for an LFE in surround music production, because all the frequencies are available in all the main channels.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] These labels sometimes use the LFE channel to carry a height channel.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The label BIS Records generally uses a 5.0 channel mix.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Channel notation indicates the number of discrete channels encoded in the audio signal, not necessarily the number of channels reproduced for playback.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The number of playback channels can be increased by using matrix decoding.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The number of playback channels may also differ from the number of speakers used to reproduce them if one or more channels drive a group of speakers.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Notation represents the number of channels, not the number of speakers.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The first digit in 5.1 is the number of full-range channels.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The .1 reflects the limited frequency range of the LFE channel.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] An alternative notation shows the number of full-range channels in front of the listener, separated by a slash from the number of full-range channels beside or behind the listener, with a decimal point marking the number of limited-range LFE channels.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The notation can be expanded to include Matrix Decoders.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Dolby Digital EX, for example, has a sixth full-range channel incorporated into the two rear channels with a matrix.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The term stereo, although popularised in reference to two-channel audio, historically also referred to surround sound, as it strictly means *solid* (three-dimensional) sound.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] However, this is no longer common usage, and *stereo sound* almost exclusively means two channels, left and right.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] In 2002, Dolby premiered a master of *We Were Soldiers* which featured a Sonic Whole Overhead Sound soundtrack.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] This mix included a new ceiling-mounted height channel.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Several speaker configurations are commonly used for consumer equipment.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] While it is possible to build any speaker configuration, there is little commercial movie or music content for alternative speaker configurations.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] However, source channels can be remixed for the speaker channels using a matrix table specifying how much of each content channel is played through each speaker channel.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Most channel configurations may include an LFE channel (the channel played through the subwoofer.) This makes the configuration .1 instead of .0.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Most modern multichannel mixes contain one LFE; some use two.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] 7.1 surround sound is a popular format in theaters and home cinema, including Blu-rays with Dolby and DTS being major players.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] 7.1.2 and 7.1.4 immersive sound, along with 5.1.2 and 5.1.4 formats, add either 2 or 4 overhead speakers to enable sound objects and special effect sounds to be panned overhead for the listener.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Introduced for theatrical film releases in 2012 by Dolby Laboratories under the trademark name Dolby Atmos.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] Dolby Atmos (and other Microsoft Spatial Sound engines; see `AudioObjectType` in `SpatialAudioClient.h`) additionally support a virtual 8.1.4.4 configuration, to be rendered by a HRTF.
[src:ambisonics/surround-sound] The configuration adds to 7.1.4 with a center speaker behind the listener and 4 speakers below.
